# fleet.conf.example -- fleet.conf template for run_awr_fleet.sh
#
# Copy this file to fleet.conf (gitignored -- see .gitignore) and fill in
# your real connect strings.  run_awr_fleet.sh reads it as:
#
#   alias|connect
#
# one entry per line.
#
#   alias    a short label for this DB in the combined report and its
#            drill-down command.  Must match [A-Za-z0-9_.-]{1,30} and be
#            unique within the file -- no spaces, no pipe.
#   connect  anything sqlplus -S -L accepts after "sqlplus": user/pw@svc,
#            a bare TNS alias, '/', '/@tns_alias', or '/ as sysdba'
#            (quoting is handled for you; do not add your own quotes here).
#            Must not contain a literal single quote, tab, or newline.
#
# Blank lines and lines starting with '#' (leading whitespace allowed) are
# ignored.
#
# --- Wallet auth is strongly recommended for a fleet file ------------------
# fleet.conf commonly lists many production databases in one place.  Prefer
# an Oracle wallet + tnsnames alias per DB (SQLNET.WALLET_LOCATION, an
# auto-login wallet, TWO_TASK/TNS_ADMIN pointing at it) so this file never
# holds a plaintext password:
#
#   prod_east|/@prod_east_tns
#   prod_west|/@prod_west_tns
#
# A bare user/pw@svc line works too (below) but the password sits in this
# file in plaintext -- fine for a throwaway ad-hoc file, not for anything
# checked in or shared.  run_awr_fleet.sh masks it in every report and log
# line (user/***@svc) but the source file itself is not encrypted.
#
# --- Examples ----------------------------------------------------------
# prod_east|/@prod_east_tns
# prod_west|/@prod_west_tns
# reporting|readonly_user/change_me@reporting_svc
# staging|/@staging_tns
# dr_site|/ as sysdba
